Note:
CSS Round-Trip Translation Test Suite

Total Tests: 12
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/css/hir_to_css.runa" as ToCSS
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

@Reasoning:
Counter triple shared by the CSS round-trip driver. Matches the layout
of the parser and to-HIR suites so a unified runner can swap test
binaries with no struct conversion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
total at offset 0, passed at 8, failed at 16; mutated via raw
Layout.memory_set_int64 because results is shared by handle.
@End Implementation

Type called "TestResults":
    total as Integer
    passed as Integer
    failed as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Drives 12 CSS -> HIR -> CSS round-trip checks covering selector forms
(type, class, ID, multi-target, descendant, child combinator),
pseudo-class/pseudo-element notation, at-rules, comments, and color
literals. Any emitter rule that loses information surfaces as a
re-parse failure on the second leg.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialize TestResults, print banner, then call test_round_trip with
each inline CSS snippet. Print summary and return 1 if any test failed
else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "div { color: red; }" -> parse->HIR->emit->parse->HIR succeeds
- ".container { width: 100%; }" -> class selector preserved
- "@import url(\"test.css\");" -> at-rule round-trips intact
- "/* Comment */" -> comments survive emit
- ".box { background: #fff; }" -> color literal preserved
- Any malformed snippet -> "Initial parse failed", exit 1
@End TestCases

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be a value of type TestResults with total as 0, passed as 0, failed as 0

    proc print_header

    proc test_round_trip with "div { color: red; }", "Simple rule", results
    proc test_round_trip with ".container { width: 100%; }", "Class selector", results
    proc test_round_trip with "#main { padding: 20px; }", "ID selector", results
    proc test_round_trip with "h1, h2 { margin: 0; }", "Multiple selectors", results
    proc test_round_trip with "body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }", "Multiple declarations", results
    proc test_round_trip with "a:hover { color: blue; }", "Pseudo-class", results
    proc test_round_trip with "p::before { content: \"-\"; }", "Pseudo-element", results
    proc test_round_trip with "div > p { margin-left: 10px; }", "Child combinator", results
    proc test_round_trip with "@import url(\"test.css\");", "At-rule", results
    proc test_round_trip with "/* Comment */", "Comment", results
    proc test_round_trip with ".box { background: #fff; }", "Color value", results
    proc test_round_trip with ".grid { display: grid; }", "Display property", results

    proc print_results from results

    If results.failed is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Performs parse -> HIR -> emit -> re-parse -> HIR for one CSS fragment.
Both legs must reach HIR for the test to pass, proving the emitter
produced syntactically valid CSS that round-trips through the parser.
Unlike the C# variant, this suite does not allocate a separate arena
because translate_css_to_hir accepts a 0 arena and uses its own scratch
allocator internally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Increment results.total.
2. parse_css(source) -> ast1; null -> "Initial parse failed".
3. translate_css_to_hir(source, 0) -> hir1; null -> "Translation to HIR failed".
4. generate_css(hir1) -> generated; null -> "Generation from HIR failed".
5. parse_css(generated) -> ast2; null -> free generated, "Re-parse failed".
6. translate_css_to_hir(generated, 0) -> hir2; null -> free generated,
   "Re-translation to HIR failed".
7. Success: free generated, mark passed.
Note: each failure path tracks the exact buffers allocated up to that
point so deallocation is balanced.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "div { color: red; }" -> all six stages succeed
- ")(not css" -> ast1 == 0 -> "Initial parse failed"
- Emitter drops braces -> ast2 == 0 -> "Re-parse failed"
- Translator returns 0 on second pass -> hir2 == 0 -> "Re-translation to HIR failed"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip" takes source as Integer, test_name as Integer, results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let _rtot1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 0, _rtot1 plus 1

    Let ast1 be proc parse_css from Parser with source

    If ast1 is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Initial parse failed"
        Let _rfal1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal1 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir1 be proc translate_css_to_hir from ToHIR with source, 0

    If hir1 is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Translation to HIR failed"
        Let _rfal2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal2 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let generated be proc generate_css from ToCSS with hir1

    If generated is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Generation from HIR failed"
        Let _rfal3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal3 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast2 be proc parse_css from Parser with generated

    If ast2 is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Re-parse failed"
        proc deallocate from Layout with generated
        Let _rfal4 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal4 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir2 be proc translate_css_to_hir from ToHIR with generated, 0

    If hir2 is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Re-translation to HIR failed"
        proc deallocate from Layout with generated
        Let _rfal5 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal5 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with generated

    proc print_test_success from test_name
    Let _rpas1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 8, _rpas1 plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Banner once at startup. Separator width (39 "=") matches the title
length so the heading boxes neatly in CI log output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate title and "=" rule via StringCore, print each, deallocate.
Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_header" returns Integer:
    Let header be proc create_string from StringCore with "CSS Round-Trip Translation Test Suite"
    proc print from header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with "======================================="
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[PASS] <name>" line. Identical format to peer CSS suites so unified
greps work across the language family.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[PASS] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned test_name,
deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_success" takes test_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pass_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[PASS] "
    proc print from pass_msg
    proc print from test_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with pass_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[FAIL] <name>: <reason>" line. reason identifies the exact round-trip
stage that broke (initial parse, translate, emit, re-parse, re-translate)
so failure logs pinpoint the responsible component.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[FAIL] " prefix, print prefix/test_name/": "/reason in order,
then deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_failure" takes test_name as Integer, reason as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fail_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[FAIL] "
    proc print from fail_msg
    proc print from test_name
    proc print with ": "
    proc print from reason
    proc deallocate from Layout with fail_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final summary block. Reads counters through type-checked struct field
access (results.total etc.) at the report site, complementing the raw
memory_get_int64 path used inside test_round_trip.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print "=" separator, "Test Results:" heading, then Total/Passed/Failed
lines. Each label allocated/printed/deallocated; numbers via print_int.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with "======================================="
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let summary be proc create_string from StringCore with "Test Results:"
    proc print from summary
    proc deallocate from Layout with summary

    Let total_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Total: "
    proc print from total_msg
    proc print_int with results.total
    proc deallocate from Layout with total_msg

    Let passed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Passed: "
    proc print from passed_msg
    proc print_int with results.passed
    proc deallocate from Layout with passed_msg

    Let failed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Failed: "
    proc print from failed_msg
    proc print_int with results.failed
    proc deallocate from Layout with failed_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local integer formatter so this suite has no dependency on stdlib
formatting allocators. Handles zero and negative inputs explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. value == 0 -> print "0", return.
2. Allocate 32-byte buffer; walk position from 31 downward, writing
   48 + (temp % 10) and dividing temp by 10.
3. For negatives, operate on -temp; write '-' (45) at final position.
4. Increment position, print buffer+position as a C string, deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_int" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Let zero be proc create_string from StringCore with "0"
        proc print from zero
        proc deallocate from Layout with zero
        Return 1
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let position be 31
    Let temp be value

    If temp is less than 0:
        Set temp to -temp
    End If

    While temp is greater than 0:
        Let digit be temp modulo by 10
        Let char be 48 plus digit
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, char
        Set position to position minus 1
        Set temp to temp divided by 10
    End While

    If value is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, 45
        Set position to position minus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    Let str_ptr be buffer plus position
    proc print from str_ptr

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of CSS Round-Trip Translation Test Suite
